The paper deals with graph reduction and optimization, which are topics that are commonly studied in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of local conditions to preserve graph classes suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), while the focus on finding the maximum number of edges in a planar graph suggests a connection to graph theory (cs.GT). Finally, the mention of "side effects" and "non-deterministic" and "non-confluent" reductions suggests a connection to software engineering and programming languages (cs.SI).
